\n\nThe current time is 10:05 AM, but that's probably just context. The main thing is the workflow.\n\nBut the user's instruction says \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\" So the agent should output the result of the queue check, but since it's a cron task, the summary would be the status of the queue processing.\n\nWait, the task says: \"If the task explicitly calls for messaging a specific external recipient, note who/where it should go instead of sending it yourself.\" But in this case, it's a cron job to process the queue, so the summary should be the status of processing.\n\nThe user might want a log of what happened: if there were requests, how many processed, etc.\n\nBut since the agent is img-gen-5, it should just follow the steps. Let me structure the response.\n\nFirst, check the queue. If there's a request, process it. If not, say the queue is empty.\n\nAssuming there's a request, the steps would be:\n\n1. Claim request: node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-5 → gets request JSON.\n2. Get profile ID: use the node command to read google-accounts.json.\n3. Refine prompt using the guide.\n4. Generate image in Gemini.\n5. Mark complete with img-complete.js.\n\nAfter processing, check again.\n\nBut the response should be a summary. So if there were requests, the summary would state that a request was processed. If not, \"Queue empty.\"\n\nWait, the user's cron job says: \"Run: node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-5 — if a request is returned (not null), process it following your SOUL.md workflow. Generate the image in Gemini, download it, call img-complete.js when done, then check the queue again for more pending requests.\"\n\nSo the agent must execute the claim command, process any found requests, then loop until empty.\n\nIn the response, the agent should report the outcome. Since the user is expecting a summary, maybe the agent will output the result of the queue check, but the task says \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nBut the agent is in a cron job, so it's supposed to run the process and send the summary. So the agent should:\n\n- Run the claim command.\n- If request exists, process it.\n- Then, if there's more, check again.\n- Finally, report the number of processed requests.\n\nBut how to do this in a cron job? Since the user provided the cron command, the agent needs to follow it.\n\nWait, the agent is img-gen-5, so it should execute the steps outlined in SOUL.md.\n\nBut the user is asking for a summary. So the agent should check the queue, process any requests, and report the results.\n\nThe actual task is to run the claim.js script, and if there's a request, process it. So the agent's job is to do that.\n\nTherefore, the agent should first run the claim command. Let's assume it returns a request.\n\nThen, process it according to the steps. Then, check again.\n\nBut since this is a summary, the agent would report that a request was processed, and how many.\n\nAlternatively, if the queue is empty, it would say \"Queue empty.\"\n\nBut given that the cron job is for checking, the agent should output whether any requests were processed.\n\nSo the response should be something like: \"Queue checked. Processed 1 request. Images generated: image-1.png.\"\n\nOr, if no requests, \"Queue empty.\"\n\nBut in the user's message, they provided the cron command, so the agent must follow it.\n\nThe agent needs to call the tool to execute the claim command.\n\nWait, the user is asking the agent to run the command and provide a summary.\n\nSo the agent's response should be the output of the command execution.\n\nBut since the agent has the tools available, it needs to use exec to run the node command.\n\nSo first step: run node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-5.\n\nIf the output is a JSON object (request), then process it. If it's null, queue is empty.\n\nThe agent should call the exec tool to run the command.\n\nLet's simulate:\n\nexec co